**user**:
> How can I ask my academic advisor to consider nominating me for an award?
**assistant**:
> Hello James,
> 
> Approaching your academic advisor for award nomination might seem tricky, but remember, an open and professional chat can help resolve most of your concerns. Here is a rough draft of how you could structure your email:
> 
> ---
> 
> Subject: Requesting Your Consideration for Award Nomination
> 
> Dear [Advisor's Name],
> 
> I hope this message finds you well. I would like to discuss a matter that is of importance to me.
> 
> It has come to my attention that the application period for [the name of the award] is quickly approaching. This award resonates strongly with my academic and research goals, and I believe that my body of work aligns with the criteria and vision of [the award name].
> 
> Over the course of my work on [summarize relevant projects or research], I have been consistently dedicated, learned a great deal, and made important contributions such as [briefly mention significant results or findings]. I feel that these achievements demonstrate my potential and commitment to [the field of study or research].
> 
> Given our working relationship, and your familiarity with my dedication and accomplishments, I am hoping that you would consider nominating me for this award. I truly believe that your recommendation would hold great value.
> 
> Should you need any further details about my work, or if there is any additional information required for the nomination, I would be more than willing to provide it.
> 
> I appreciate your consideration and look forward to your response.
> 
> Best regards,
> 
> [Your Name]
> 
> ---
> 
> Remember, your advisor is there to support you and wants to see you succeed. Good luck!
